{"add":{"doc":{"id":"0b2fa69e99f2d328483a882c4fec5140e9bc648cd40836620d46b4e0b3bfd509","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/47/Glennon_Hands_off_to_Ore_2007_ECU_crop.jpg/220px-Glennon_Hands_off_to_Ore_2007_ECU_crop.jpg","previous":[],"after":["Virginia is the most populous U.S. state without a major professional sports league franchise.[298] The reasons for this include the lack of any dominant city or market within the state, the proximity of teams in Washington, D.C. and North Carolina, and a reluctance to publicly finance stadiums.[299][300] Norfolk is host to the two highest-level minor league teams in the state: The AAA Norfolk Tides and the AHL's Norfolk Admirals, winners of the 2012 Calder Cup.[301] The San Francisco Giants' AA team, the Richmond Flying Squirrels, began play at The Diamond in 2010, replacing the AAA Richmond Braves, who relocated after 2008.[302] Additionally, the Washington Nationals, Boston Red Sox, Seattle Mariners, Chicago White Sox, and Atlanta Braves also have Single-A and Rookie-level farm teams in Virginia.[303]"]}}}